In .NET MAUI, lifecycle management moved from `Application` to `Window`. You have two options:

**Option 1: Override methods on a custom Window**

```csharp
public class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new MyWindow(new MainPage());
}

public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* was OnStart */ }
    protected override void OnStopped()    { /* was OnSleep */ }
    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* was OnResume */ }
}
```

**Option 2: Subscribe to Window events in `CreateWindow`**

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = new Window(new MainPage());
    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart */ };
    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep */ };
    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume */ };
    return window;
}
```

**Mapping summary:**
| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window |
|--------------|-----------------|
| `OnStart`    | `Created` / `OnCreated` |
| `OnSleep`    | `Stopped` / `OnStopped` |
| `OnResume`   | `Resumed` / `OnResumed` |

The `Window` class also exposes `Activated`, `Deactivated`, and `Destroying` for finer-grained control.
